OL,3,CChancellor may reduce spending by #6bn
OL,4,Cto help fund 2p cut in NI or income tax
OL,6,FHere is the basic math that confronts
OL,7,FHunt.JThe so-called "headroom" for any
OL,8,Ftax cuts or spending increases, were
OL,9,Fhe to do nothing at all, would be
OL,10,Faround #13 billion. That's what the
OL,11,Flatest still-confidential forecast of
OL,12,Fthe Office for Budget Responsibility
OL,13,Fsays.JAs I understand it, the
OL,14,FChancellor has decided that, in the
OL,15,Fexceptional circumstances of a looming
OL,16,Fgeneral election and a stagnating
OL,17,Feconomy, it would be just-about
OL,18,Facceptable to reduce that headroom to
OL,19,F#6bn.JHeadroom of #6 billion is low by
OL,20,Fhistorical standards, but Hunt feels
OL,21,Fit would be defendable - just.JThis
OL,22,F"headroom" is the monetary buffer that
OL,23,Fexists to absorb unexpected calls on
OL,24,Fthe public finances, such that debt as
OL,25,Fa share of GDP, or national income,
OL,26,Ffalls marginally in five year's time,
OL,1,Wz5~k4~k7}hw1 ~k4~sj5j5~s1 G     G3/10
